1 1. Cooperate with landowners, state agencies, and other
2 political subdivisions for removal of harmful woody species;
3 2. Measure the density of harmful woody species and estimate
4 water used by those species;
5 3. Create a study using a parallel watershed with no control of
6 harmful woody species;
7 4. Utilize available funds to cost-share with landowners,
8 recognized governmental entities, or not-for-profit organizations
9 for expenses incurred in the eradication of harmful woody species by
10 prescribed burn, biological controls, mechanical removal, or
11 herbicide applications;
12 5. Develop grant programs with conservation districts, rural
13 fire departments, and prescribe burn associations for resources
14 needed for prescribed burns, mechanical removal, biological control,
15 or herbicide applications on harmful woody species;
16 6. Bring attention to the problems posed by harmful woody
17 species to create awareness, demonstrate value to all stakeholders,
18 and encourage landowners to participate in the program; and
19 7. Have at least two three active project areas in the program,
20 consisting either of one above the Canton Lake dam and one below,
21 above Lake Overholser, and the North Fork Red River into Lugert-
22 Altus Reservoir.
23 D. The Commission is authorized to promulgate any rules and
24 procedures to effectuate the provisions of this section.
